&gt; --- In archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com, Gordon Mohr &lt;gojomo@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt; The &#39;Key&#39; mechanism is for configurable settings, rather than dynamic 
&gt;&gt; state that varies for different URIs.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Instead use the getData() method of CrawlURI to get a 
&gt;&gt; HashMap&lt;String,Object&gt; into which you can store arbitrary state for 
&gt;&gt; later Processors.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; (This data doesn&#39;t survive the URI being put back onto a queue -- for 
&gt;&gt; example if it needs to be retried after certain kinds of errors. For 
&gt;&gt; that, or for data that should be &#39;inherited&#39; by other URIs discovered 
&gt;&gt; via the current CrawlURI, look at the addPersistentDataMapKey() or 
&gt;&gt; makeHeritable() methods. If using either of these, make sure the extra 
&gt;&gt; state you add serializes/deserializes cleanly.)
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Also, do you need particular features only present in Heritrix 2.0.2? If 
&gt;&gt; not, I recommend using 1.14.3; it is still better documented and more 
&gt;&gt; proven in production environments than the 2.0.x line.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; In 1.14.3, the same general mechanisms exist but the implementing 
&gt;&gt; methods/classes are slightly different:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; 2.0.x                        1.14.3
&gt;&gt; getData()                 -&gt; getAlist()
&gt;&gt; addPersistentDataMapKey() -&gt; addAlistPersistentMember()
&gt;&gt; makeHeritable()           -&gt; makeHeritable()
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; - Gordon @ IA
